<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
Gate 2 — notFound: no GIS candidate on either layer.

Both the SSAP and RCL progressive filters exhaust all available records without
producing a single candidate. This is distinct from a stop-on-first-invalid result
(where at least some elements validated before failure). Here, the submitted street
name "Phantom" does not exist in any provisioned GIS record for Bismarck; both
filters produce an empty candidate set after evaluating ca:RD.

The expected outcome is a non-conforming locationValidation result with ca:RD as
<invalid> (stop-on-first-invalid fires at the street name level after A3 validates
successfully) and remaining submitted elements in <unchecked>. The civic coverage
region lookup selects the correct PSAP boundary based on the validated admin
elements (country, A1, A2, A3).

Note: pure <notFound> (zero candidates on all layers with no invalid element) requires
both layers to be completely empty or exhausted with 2+ ambiguous candidates. The more
common real-world scenario — and the one tested here — is an invalid at a sub-A3 level
with a successful coverage region fallback for <mapping> selection.
-->
<findService xmlns="urn:ietf:params:xml:ns:lost1" validateLocation="true">
  <location id="L1" profile="civic">
    <civicAddress xmlns="urn:ietf:params:xml:ns:pidf:geopriv10:civicAddr">
      <country>US</country>
      <A1>ND</A1>
      <A2>Burleigh County</A2>
      <A3>Bismarck</A3>
      <RD>Phantom</RD>
      <STS>Avenue</STS>
      <HNO>100</HNO>
    </civicAddress>
  </location>
  <service>urn:service:sos</service>
</findService>
